AB  - Fibromyalgia (FM) is a chronic illness characterized by widespread pain and multiple associated symptoms. Nurse practitioners (NPs), as primary care providers (PCP), play a crucial role in recognizing and managing misconceptions about FM, as a low index of suspicion can delay diagnosis and treatment. When patients feel dismissed, they may experience a lack of validation, frustration, and inadequate care, worsening their health outcomes. This article offers NPs evidence-based knowledge to enhance their understanding of FM, reduce diagnostic delays, improve patient education, and implement interdisciplinary strategies. By leading care teams, NPs can significantly improve outcomes and the quality of life for individuals with FM. • Fibromyalgia (FM) is chronic widespread musculoskeletal pain and tenderness. • The pathophysiological hallmark of FM is central sensitization. • The complexities of FM are most effectively managed by an interdisciplinary team. • Recommendations are that primary care providers lead the interdisciplinary teams. • Evidence-based literature guides the diagnosis, management, and treatment of FM.
